e genre, particularly in, but not limited to, an English context. Topics covered include genre and literary classification; race and ethnicity; gender; orality and performance; the romance and young readers; metre and form; printing culture; and reception. CONTRIBUTORS: ROSALIND FIELD, RALUCA L. RADULESCU, MALDWYN MILLS, GILLIAN ROGERS, JENNIFER FELLOWS, THOMAS H. CROFTS, ROBERT ALLEN ROUSE, JOANNE CHARBONNEAU,DESIREE CROMWELL, AD PUTTER, KARL REICHL, PHILLIPA HARDMAN, CORY JAMES RUSHTON  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyxHistory and criticismzEngland. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular literaturexHistory and criticismzEngland. 0aPopular literaturezEnglandxHistory and criticism. 0aRomancesxHistory and criticism. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAd Putter.  aChivalric adventure.  aCory James Rushton.  aDesiree Cromwell.  aEthnicity.  aForm.  aGender.  aGenre.  aGillian Rogers.  aJennifer Fellows.  aJoanne Charbonneau.  aKarl Reichl.  aLiterary Classification.  aMaldwyn Mills.  aMedieval Popular Romance.  aMedieval.  aMetre.  aMiddle Ages.  aMonsters.  aOrality.  aPerformance.  aPhillipa Hardman.  aPopular romance.  aPrinting Culture.  aPrinting culture.  aRace.  aRaluca L. Radulescu.  aReception.  aRobert Allen Rouse.  aRosalind Field.  aSaintly women.  aThomas H. Crofts.  aYoung Readers.1 aCharbonneau, Joanne A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharbonneau, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/